                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <origDate notBefore="1800" notAfter="1899"/>
                            <note>The manuscript was written by at least two scribes, <persName ref="PRS14637HabtaGi" role="scribe">Habta Giyorgis</persName> (mentioned on 
                                <locus target="#94v"/>) and <persName role="scribe" ref="PRS14638WaldaTH">Walda Takla Hāymānot</persName> (mentioned on <locus target="#97r"/>).
                                The manuscript belonged to several inviduals, whose names are mentioned throughout the text.
                                The name of <persName role="owner" ref="PRS14639WaldaIy">Walda ʾIyasus</persName> occurs on <locus target="#98r #99r #103r #110v"/>, 
                                together with that of his son <persName ref="PRS14640GabraWa">Gabra Wald</persName> on <locus target="#97r"/>.
                                The name of another owner, that of <persName role="owner" ref="PRS14641GabraSe">Gabra Śǝllāse</persName>, is sometimes inserted in a 
                                rudimentary hand, mostly interlineally, except on <locus target="#111v"/>, where a blank space had been left. 
                                His name is also added in a secondary hand in the supplications on <locus target="#94v #97r"/>.
                                Finally, another name, that of <persName role="owner" ref="PRS14642TaklaMa">Takla Māryām</persName>, is found in the lower margin of 
                                <locus target="#111r"/>. 
                          </note>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>According to the account on the manuscripts’ provenance given by Eugène Tisserant, this manuscript is among those
                            acquired by <persName ref="PRS4805Grebaut" role="owner"/> in <date when="1925"/> with funds of
                            <persName ref="PRS14055SaintJ">Jean Saint</persName>. 
                            The manuscripts originated from Šawā (ʾAddis ʾAbabā, Dabra Libānos, Dabra Bǝrhān),
                            Goǧǧām (Dimā Giyorgis, Marṭula Māryām, Dabra Warq) and Bagemdǝr (Gondar, ʾAzazo Takla Hāymānot) and very few from Tǝgrāy.
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition when="1928">The manuscript entered the library on <date>18 April 1928</date>.</acquisition>
